---
<Base
  title="About Tipsheet — why it exists, and who built it"
  description="Why Tipsheet exists, who's behind it, and how the most important filings from India's listed companies become short, readable news. Made by Bhuvan."
>
  <Masthead />
  <main>
    <article class="prose-page">
      <header>
        <div class="kicker"><span>About</span></div>
        <h1 class="page-title">Why I built this.</h1>
      </header>

      <hr class="rule" />

      <p>
        I'll start with the part that bothers me. Financial news in India is, for the most part, bad. Not bad in the ordinary way most things are slightly bad — bad in a way that's almost a feat. Routine, formulaic stories that should take an afternoon to get right come out padded, garbled, or simply wrong. After enough years of reading it, you stop being irritated and start being a little impressed. It begins to look like performance art.
      </p>
      <p>
        I care about this more than is probably healthy. I love old-fashioned journalism — the patient, unglamorous kind — and I think good reporting does something real for the place it covers. So watching it done badly, again and again, has always nagged at me. I wanted to be a journalist once. Better sense prevailed.
      </p>
      <p>
        Instead I've spent years tinkering with small ways to put better information in front of people. <a href="https://smallweb.blog/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">smallweb.blog</a>, my most recent site. <a href="https://www.rabbitholes.garden/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">rabbitholes.garden</a>, where I keep a link blog of things worth your time. A few other things still half-finished. It's the same itch every time.
      </p>
      <p>
        I work in finance, so financial journalism is the corner of all this that depresses me most, and the urge to do something about it never quite went away. So I started small, and specific.
      </p>
      <p>
        Some very good colleagues of mine have been living inside AI for a while, and they built a pipeline that reads every exchange filing from Indian companies and surfaces the handful that genuinely matter. They handed me the feed. I did the obvious thing with it: pointed another language model at each important filing and had it write the thing up properly — short, plain, readable. That's the whole origin of Tipsheet.
      </p>
      <p>
        So here's what you get. Short pieces on the most consequential news from India's listed companies. Not all of it — I'm not republishing every filing from every company. Only the ones that clear a real bar for importance make it here. Think of them as alerts worth your attention.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you'll allow me a moment of arrogance: I think these are already better than what most of the field puts out. And in the same honest breath — they're still just alerts. I have bigger plans for where this goes. This is simply where it starts.
      </p>

      <h2>A few things this isn't</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>It won't tell you what to buy or sell. No tips, no targets, no "calls."</li>
        <li>It carries no ads, no sponsorships, no advertorials.</li>
        <li>It doesn't rewrite anyone else's reporting. Every story comes from the company's own filing, and links back to it so you can check me.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        If you want the mechanics — what gets published, where the facts come from, and how the AI is kept honest — it's all in the <a href="/methodology/">methodology</a>.
      </p>

      <h2 id="founder">Who's behind it</h2>
      <p>
        Just me — Bhuvan. I built it, I run it, and I'll answer for it. You can find me on my <a href="https://bebhuvan.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">personal site</a>, <a href="https://bhuvan.substack.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Substack</a>, <a href="https://twitter.com/bebhuvan" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Twitter</a>, and <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/bebhuvan/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">LinkedIn</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>Start reading</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/filings/">The Wire</a> — everything published, newest first.</li>
        <li><a href="/companies/">Companies</a> — the running record for every company tracked.</li>
